        "creation_date": 1476267274,
        "body": "<p>Simple because your array has length 10 so the maximum index is 9. Arrays in Java are 0-based. It means, that it's indexes are from <code>0 incl<\/code> to <code>array.length - 1 incl<\/code> which in your case is <code>9<\/code>. <\/p>\n\n<p>Java gave you a stacktrace. It looks like following (by the way, <strong>A L W A Y S<\/strong> attach it to the question about <code>Exception<\/code>s):<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>java.lang.ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException: 10\nat package.ClassName.methodName(ClassName.java:lineNumber)\n...\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Is the line number the number of line in which you call <code>currentVal = array[i];<\/code>? If yes, it's your answer - <code>i<\/code> is <code>10<\/code>.<\/p>\n\n<p>If you paste your <code>stack trace<\/code>, comment my answer for further help. I'll answer with pleasure.<\/p>\n",
